<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Blog Detail</title>
    <style>
        /* ---- GLOBAL ---- */
        * {
            box-sizing: border-box;
            margin: 0;
            padding: 0;
        }

        body {
            font-family: 'Arial', sans-serif;
            background-color: #f4f4f4;
            line-height: 1.6;
        }

        /* ---- NAVBAR ---- */
        .navbar {
            width: 100%;
            background-color: #333;
            padding: 15px 30px;
            display: flex;
            justify-content: space-between;
            align-items: center;
        }

        .navbar .logo {
            color: #ffcc00;
            font-size: 24px;
            font-weight: bold;
        }

        .navbar ul {
            list-style: none;
            display: flex;
        }

        .navbar ul li {
            margin-left: 25px;
        }

        .navbar ul li a {
            color: #fff;
            text-decoration: none;
            font-size: 16px;
            transition: color 0.3s;
        }

        .navbar ul li a:hover {
            color: #ffcc00;
        }

        /* ---- BLOG DETAIL ---- */
        .blog-container {
            width: 90%;
            max-width: 800px;
            margin: 50px auto;
            background-color: #fff;
            border-radius: 12px;
            overflow: hidden;
            box-shadow: 0 10px 25px rgba(0,0,0,0.1);
        }

        .blog-image {
            width: 100%;
            height: 300px;
            object-fit: cover;
        }

        .blog-content {
            padding: 30px;
        }

        .blog-title {
            font-size: 32px;
            font-weight: bold;
            margin-bottom: 10px;
            color: #222;
        }

        .blog-meta {
            font-size: 14px;
            color: #888;
            margin-bottom: 20px;
            display: flex;
            justify-content: space-between;
        }

        .blog-description {
            font-size: 18px;
            color: #555;
            margin-bottom: 30px;
        }

        .back-button {
            padding: 12px 25px;
            border: none;
            border-radius: 6px;
            background-color: #ffcc00;
            color: #333;
            font-weight: bold;
            cursor: pointer;
            text-decoration: none;
            transition: background-color 0.3s;
        }

        .back-button:hover {
            background-color: #e6b800;
        }

        /* ---- FOOTER ---- */
        .footer {
            background-color: #333;
            color: #fff;
            text-align: center;
            padding: 20px;
            margin-top: 50px;
        }

        /* RESPONSIVE */
        @media(max-width:768px){
            .blog-title{
                font-size:28px;
            }
            .blog-description{
                font-size:16px;
            }
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

    <!-- NAVBAR -->
    <div class="navbar">
        <div class="logo">My Blog</div>
        <ul>
            <li><a href="index.html">Home</a></li>
            <li><a href="#">About</a></li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- BLOG DETAIL -->
    <div class="blog-container">
        <img src="https://source.unsplash.com/800x400/?coding" alt="Blog Image" class="blog-image">
        <div class="blog-content">
            <div class="blog-title">Understanding JavaScript Closures</div>
            <div class="blog-meta">
                <span>Author: John Doe</span>
                <span>Jan 12, 2025</span>
            </div>
            <div class="blog-description">
                <p>
                    JavaScript closures are an important concept that allows functions to access variables from an outer function scope even after that outer function has finished executing. Closures are often used for data encapsulation, callbacks, and functional programming techniques.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Example:
                    <br>
                    <code>
                        function outer(){ <br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;let count = 0;<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;return function(){<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;count++;<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;console.log(count);<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;}<br>
                        }<br>
                        const counter = outer();<br>
                        counter(); // 1<br>
                        counter(); // 2
                    </code>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Closures allow you to maintain private variables and create more modular, reusable code.
                </p>
            </div>
            <a href="index.html" class="back-button">Back to Home</a>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- FOOTER -->
    <div class="footer">
        &copy; 2025 My Blog. All Rights Reserved.
    </div>

</body>
</html>
